.TH emacs 1
.SH NAME
.PP
\*Lemacs\*O, \*Lxemacs\*O \- GNU project Emacs
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\*Lemacs\*O [\*Vcommand-line switches\*O] [\*Vfile ...\*O]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.iX "editor" "emacs"
.iX "emacs"
.iX "GNU emacs"
.iX "xemacs"
.iX "text editor" "emacs"
\*LGNU Emacs\*O is a new version of \*LEmacs\*O, written by the author
of the original (PDP-10) \*LEmacs,\*O Richard Stallman.
Its user functionality encompasses  everything other \*LEmacs\*O
editors do, and it is easily extensible since its editing commands are
written in Lisp.
.PP
\*LEmacs\*O has an extensive interactive help facility, but to use it
you must know how to manipulate \*LEmacs\*O windows and buffers.
\*CCTRL-h\*O (backspace or CTRL-h) enters the Help facility.
\*CHelp Tutorial\*O (CTRL-h t) requests an interactive tutorial which
can teach beginners the fundamentals of \*LEmacs\*O in a few minutes.
\*CHelp Apropos\*O (CTRL-h a) helps you find a command given its
functionality, \*CHelp Character\*O (Ctrl-h c) describes a given
character's effect, and \*CHelp Function\*O (CTRL-h f) describes a
given Lisp function specified by name.
.PP
\*LEmacs\*O's \*CUndo\*O command can undo several steps of
modification to your buffers, so it is easy to recover from editing
mistakes.
.\" .PP
.\" \*VGNU Emacs's\*O
.\" many special packages handle mail reading (RMail) and sending (Mail),
.\" outline editing (Outline), compiling (Compile), running subshells
.\" within
.\" \*LEmacs\*O
.\" windows (Shell), running a Lisp read-eval-print loop
.\" (Lisp-Interaction-Mode), and automated psychotherapy (Doctor).
.PP
There is an extensive reference manual, but users of other Emacses
should have little trouble adapting even without a copy.
Users new to \*LEmacs\*O will be able to use basic features fairly
rapidly by studying the tutorial and using the self-documentation
features.
.PP
.SS "General Emacs Options"
The following options are of general interest:
.VL 6m
.LI "\*Vfile\*O"
Edit \*Vfile\*O.
.LI "\*L\+\*Vnumber\*O"
Go to the line specified by \*Vnumber\*O.
(Do not insert a space between the \*L+\*O sign and the number.)
.LI "\*L\-q\*O"
Do not load an init file.
.LI "\*L\-u \*Vuser\*O"
Load \*Vuser\*O's init file.
.LI "\*L\-t file\*O"
Use specified \*Vfile\*O
as the terminal instead of using stdin/stdout.
This must be the first argument specified in the command line.
.LE
.SS "Lisp Options"
The following options are lisp-oriented.
These options are processed in the order encountered.
.VL 6m
.LI "\*L\-f function\*O"
Execute the lisp function \*Vfunction\*O.
.LI "\*L \-l file\*O"
Load the lisp code in the file \*Vfile\*O.
.LE
.SS "Batch Options"
The following options are useful when running \*LEmacs\*O as a batch
editor:
.VL 6m
.LI "\*L\-batch \*Vcommandfile\*O"
Edit in batch mode, using the commands found in \*Vcommandfile\*O.
The editor will send messages to stdout.
This option must be the first in the argument list.
.LI "\*L\-kill\*O"
Exit \*LEmacs\*O while in batch mode.
.LE
