.SS "Using Emacs with X"
\*LEmacs\*O has been tailored to work with the X window system.
If you run \*LEmacs\*O from under X windows, it will create its own X
window in which to display.
You will probably want to start the editor as a background process
(\*Lemacs &\*O) so that you can continue using your original window.
.PP
\*LEmacs\*O
can be started with the following X switches:
.VL 6m
.LI "\*L\-rn name\*O"
Specifies the program name which should be used when looking up
defaults in the user's X resources.
This must be the first option specified in the command line.
.LI "\*L\-wn name\*O"
Specifies the name which should be assigned to the \*LEmacs\*O
window.
.LI "\*L\-r\*O"
Display the \*LEmacs\*O window in reverse video.
.LI "\*L\-i\*O"
Use the ``kitchen sink'' bitmap icon when iconifying the \*LEmacs\*O
window.
.LI "\*L\-font \*Vfont\*O, \*L\-fn \*Vfont\*O"
Set the \*LEmacs\*O window's font to that specified by \*Vfont\*O.
You will find the various \*VX\*O fonts in the
\*C/usr/lib/X11/fonts\*O directory.
.IP
Note that \*LEmacs\*O will only accept fixed-width fonts.
Under the X11 Release 4 font-naming conventions, any font with the
value ``m'' or ``c'' in the eleventh field of the font name is a fixed
width font.  Furthermore, fonts whose name are of the form
\*Vwidth x height\*O are generally fixed-width, as is the font
\*Vfixed\*O.
.\" See
.\" .IR xlsfonts (1)
.\" for more information.
.IP
When you specify a font, be sure to put a space between the
switch and the font name.
.LI "\*L\-b pixels\*O"
Set the \*LEmacs\*O window's border width to the number of pixels
specified by \*Vpixels\*O.
Defaults to one pixel on each side of the window.
.LI "\*L\-ib pixels\*O"
Set the window's internal border width to the number of pixels specified
by \*Vpixels\*O.
Defaults to one pixel of padding on each side of the window.
.LI "\*L\-w \*Vgeometry\*O, \*L\-geometry \*Vgeometry\*O"
Set the \*LEmacs\*O
window's width, height, and position as specified.
The geometry specification is in the standard X format; see
\*LX\*O(1X) for more information.
The width and height are specified in characters.
The default is 80 by 24.
.LE
.SS "Color Options"
The following options let you specify colors for an \*LEmacs\*O window
on color displays.
.VL 6m
.LI "\*L \-fg \*Vcolor\*O"
Sets the color of the text.
See the file \*C/usr/lib/X11/rgb.txt\*O for a list of valid color
names.
.LI "\*L\-bg \*Vcolor\*O"
Sets the color of the window's background.
.LI "\*L\-bd \*Vcolor\*O"
Sets the color of the window's border.
.LI "\*L\-cr \*Vcolor\*O"
Sets the color of the window's text cursor.
.LI "\*L\-ms \*Vcolor\*O"
Sets the color of the window's mouse cursor.
.LE
.SS "X Window Options"
The following options let you determine various aspects of how
\*LEmacs\*O interacts with your \*LX\*O window environment.
.VL 6m
.LI "\*L\-d \*Vdisplayname\*O,  \*L\-display \*Vdisplayname\*O"
Create the \*LEmacs\*O window on the display specified by
\*Vdisplayname\*O.
Must be the first option specified in the command line.
.LI "\*L\-nw\*O"
Tells \*LEmacs\*O not to use its special interface to X.
If you use this switch when invoking \*LEmacs\*O from an
\*Lxterm\*O(1X) window, display is done in that window.
This must be the first option specified in the command line.
.LE
.SS "X Window Keywords"
You can set \*VX\*O default values for your \*LEmacs\*O windows in
your \*L\.Xresources\*O file, using the following format:
.\" (see
.\" .IR xrdb (1)).
.iS
    emacs.keyword:value
.iE
.PP
where \*Vvalue\*O specifies the default value of \*Vkeyword\*O.
\*LEmacs\*O lets you set default values for the following keywords:
.VL 6m
.LI "\*Lfont (\*Oclass\*L Font)\*O"
Sets the window's text font.
.LI "\*LreverseVideo (\*Oclass\*L ReverseVideo)\*O"
If \*VreverseVideo\*O's value is set to \*Von\*O,
the window will be displayed in reverse video.
.LI "\*LbitmapIcon (\*Oclass\*L BitmapIcon)\*O"
If \*VbitmapIcon\*O's value is set to \*Von\*O,
the window will iconify into the ``kitchen sink.''
.LI "\*LborderWidth (\*Oclass\*L BorderWidth)\*O"
Sets the window's border width in pixels.
.LI "\*LinternalBorder (\*Oclass\*L BorderWidth)\*O"
Sets the window's internal border width in pixels.
.LI "\*Lforeground (\*Oclass\*L Foreground)\*O"
For color displays, sets the window's text color.
.LI "\*Lbackground (\*Oclass\*L Background)\*O"
For color displays, sets the window's background color.
.LI "\*LborderColor (\*Oclass\*L BorderColor)\*O"
For color displays, sets the color of the window's border.
.LI "\*LcursorColor (\*Oclass\*L Foreground)\*O"
For color displays, sets the color of the window's text cursor.
.LI "\*LpointerColor (\*Oclass\*L Foreground)\*O"
For color displays, sets the color of the window's mouse cursor.
.LI "\*Lgeometry (\*Oclass\*L Geometry)\*O"
Sets the geometry of the \*LEmacs\*O window (as described above).
.LI "\*Ltitle (\*Oclass\*L Title)\*O"
Sets the title of the \*LEmacs\*O window.
.LI "\*LiconName (\*Oclass\*L Title)\*O"
Sets the icon name for the \*LEmacs\*O window icon.
.LE
.PP
If you try to set color values while using a black and white display,
the window's characteristics will default as follows:
.nf
	\*L\(bu\*O\  The foreground color will be set to black
	\*L\(bu\*O\  The background color will be set to white
	\*L\(bu\*O\  The border color will be set to grey.
	\*L\(bu\*O\  The text and mouse cursors will be set to black.
.fi
